  "plot_summary": "[HANG0] * This month's <i>Marvel Bullpen Bulletins</i> addresses the fears of Nick Fury's demise as shown in the August issue, indicating not to worry, Fury is still alive and will next appear in next month's issue of the Avengers.&nbsp; (Of course, people who were around last month would have already known this when they read last month's issue of <i>Captain America</i>, which featured a mysteriously still-alive Nick Fury.)\n\n[HANG0] * MBB also addresses the sudden absence of Jim Steranko, who indicated he wanted an assignment on a <i>romance</i> strip, but that he hasn't been heard from since.\n\n[HANG0] * Another announcement mentions that John Romita is teaching his son, John Jr., to draw superhero books, so perhaps it won't be long before there are two Romitas on staff!\n\n[HANG0] * Also, people are clamoring for Stan and Jack to work on an Inhumans mag in 1970.\n\n[HANG0] * Again the internals of the Silver Surfer issue for the month (issue 12) would suggest that the book was published in Nov, 1970 as opposed to Oct.&nbsp; Given that the issue of <i>Nick Fury</i> that they also have listed in the database (issue 16) seems to be erroneously listed as being published this month, despite the fact that all internal evidence would suggest an August, 1970 release, I've listed it here.&nbsp; Similar errors seem to be true of both <i>Homer the Happy Ghost</i> (vol. 2) and <i>Peter the Little Pest</i>, both of which are listed in the <i>Mighty Marvel Checklist</i> for this month but do not appear in the weekly list of published books.\n\n[HANG0] * This is not an announcement, per se, but for some reason, there was no <i>Captain Marvel </i>issue this month.&nbsp; Despite the fact that the splash page small text continued to read \"Published monthly,\" it won't be until February, 1970 before the next issue is published.&nbsp; As for this month, issue 19 is listed in the \"Still on Sale\" section.\n\n[HANG0] * As for <i>Stan's Soapbox</i>, he expresses surprise at the <i>outrage</i> of so many fans complaining about the new editorial stance of dropping continued stories, and he even has to backtrack a little, indicating that it doesn't include <i>sub-plots</i>.&nbsp; But Stan does still hold the door open to restoring the status quo, indicating that:&nbsp; <i>It's still too early to tell if we're gonna wind up with egg in our faces again</i>....&nbsp; (Depends on the ongoing reader reaction, but Stan seemed genuinely surprised at the irate fans who they <i>thought</i> were telling them they were totally overdoing the continued stories.)\n\n[HANG0] * It appears that two-page letters pages are back, which I have mixed feelings about, given that I was perfectly happy with the one-pagers since it meant less reading for me (and I know they eventually shrink down to one page in the end anyway), but the expanded versions are once again here.&nbsp; This is actually another internal bit of evidence for the fact that [LINK:1969:SURFER_11|SURFER #11] might actually have been published <i>this</i> month, because I noted it was the only one of the Marvel books that had a two-page letters page.",
