  "review_text": "This month featured 11 graded stories, each in its own magazine, for a final weighted average of [SPAN: severity=info; fontsize=large; fonttype=bold; text=5.75], about a quarter point better than last month.\n\nTopped by the wonderful end of the Kang/Grandmaster trilogy in the pages of the Avengers, the only other one that was notable was <i>Iron Man</i>, largely because the story was given room to breathe.&nbsp; Sub-Mariner, Daredevil, and the Fantastic Four brought enough intrigue to the table to register at mid-grade or better, but that left six books that fell <i>below</i> average, though admittedly, all but one (Captain America) remained at least readable.\n\nThe problem is easily identified - Marvel administered a self-inflicted wound...\n\nOne of the things I'm sure you sensed in my various reviews this month was my growing frustration over the editorial decision Marvel made of \"no continued stories.\"&nbsp; I think, in particular, you can contrast my [LINK:1969:IRON_21|IRON #21] review with both [LINK:1969:CAP_121|CAP #121] and [LINK:1969:THOR_171|THOR #171] to see why the <i>Iron Man</i> issue succeeded <i>because</i> it was able to sidestep that self-imposed restriction, while both CAP and THOR were saddled with it and suffered as a consequence.\n\nIn another instance, the Daredevil story worked in <i>spite</i> of the policy because of the unique subject matter involved, but there were far too many unforced errors made to honor the policy, and if that meant sacrificing depth, well...<i>so be it</i>!\n\nThe policy seemed directly responsible for wrecking the Wrecker's return, rendered the Man-Brute debut a dud, made a farce out of the Sub-Mariner's choice to protect the surface men against the sudden attack of the Atlanteans, forced a quick end to the Chameleon's return in the pages of Spider-Man, and pulled the rug out from under the re-formed Frightful Four inside of the home of Agatha Harkness.&nbsp; All these (and perhaps others I'm not remembering just now) were forced to adhere to the policy, even if it meant the story suffered a price.&nbsp; To me, that's shortsighted and directly undermines the depth which readers so enjoy in these books.\n\nI don't know what the near-term future is for Marvel, but I have to say, I'm not a fan of this <i>at all</i> (and I'll continue to spell out why in my reviews going forward, though I imagine there will be the odd one here and there that rises to the top <i>despite</i> the constraints - we'll see).",
  "letters_page": "[HANG0] * Introduction of Eddie March, Invaders (though still unnamed), Crime-Wave, Torpedo. Agatha Harkness, Franklin Richards (name revealed), and Lorelei\n[DEVNOTE: *** INTRODUCTION_BEGIN ***\nNotes | villain | first | Man-Brute (Bart Dietzel)\nNotes | villain | first | death | Silas Cragg\nCrimson Dynamo II | villain | Milestone: (first: as Crimson Dynamo)\nNotes | first | Eddie March (boxer, as Iron Man)\nInvaders | villain | unnamed | Milestone: (first)\nNotes | villain | first | Warlock Prime (Sir Nigel Carruthers)\nNotes | villain | first | Sibyl Carruthers\nNotes | villain | first | Torpedo\nNotes | villain | first | Crime-Wave\nAgatha Harkness | Milestone: (first)\nNotes | first | villain | Lorelei\n*** INTRODUCTION_END ***]\n[DEVNOTE: *** HIGHLIGHTS_BEGIN ***]\n[HANG0] * Eddie March tries to take over Tony Stark's place as Iron Man, forgetting his own handicap.\n[HANG0] * Kang chooses the power of \"Death to the Avengers\" rather than save his beloved Ravonna.\n[HANG0] * Bruce Banner's happiness of being Hulk-free is short-lived, as the Leader tries to steal a secret weapon.\n[HANG0] * The Silver Surfer summons the energy to defeat the Abomination before the page count expires!\n[HANG0] * Namor is forced to side with the surface men to turn away an Atlantean invasion, packed in one issue.\n[HANG0] * Willie Lincoln is targeted by Torpedo before he can testify against crime boss, Crime-Wave.\n[HANG0] * Agatha Harkness chosen to watch over newly-named Franklin Richards.&nbsp; Is she governess or witch (or both)?\n[HANG0] * The <b>real</b> Magneto's return explained.\n[DEVNOTE: *** HIGHLIGHTS_END ***]",
  "ownership": "[HANG0] * The Scorpion waits for Captain America\n[HANG0] * Iron Man finds out that sinking crate was filled with <i>another</i> threat\n[HANG0] * Jane Foster returns in the pages of <i>Thor</i>\n[HANG0] * Rick Jones and his new alter ego return to the Avengers as they face a new menace\n[HANG0] * The Rhino is given another chance to face off against the Hulk\n[HANG0] * Doctor Strange returns to consult with the Sub-Mariner\n[HANG0] * The Fantastic Four try and prevent World War III\n[HANG0] * Spider-Man faces a new, hopping-mad enemy\n[HANG0] * Daredevil seeks to unmask the mysterious Crime-Wave\n[HANG0] * and the X-Men battle a fiery new opponent over the skies of Washington DC."
